<br>
My guild is in the exact same situation as yours in terms of raiding. The raid loot policy was a very very difficult one to decide upon. After much discussion among the officers and guild members, here is what we decided upon:<br>
<br>
Mostly NBG/ random but with reserved items in special need. Meaning the next plate BP that drops goes to the MT. After that, all other plate BP's will be rolled on by all plate classes present.<br>
<br>
As far as invites to raids are concerned, I think it is very wise to have a guild only loot policy unless you NEED the guests you are inviting. Let any guest know that they are there for faction only and will only get an armor drop if everyone passes. <br>
<br>
I am the guild MT and still have yet to get a BP drop since we went to this new loot policy (had two drop before the change). <br>
<br>
The officer awarded loot system will never work, too many people will feel slighted and too many people will feel that favorites will be played, whether real or not.<br>
<br>
DKP is the best way to go but it can be a very difficult transition. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=174524"> Keane Abrams </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
60 Warlord<br>
Tunare's Benevolence<br>
Zebuxoruk</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 669<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/9/03 5:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Raid loot policies and guild progression</span><hr size=1> I happen to think that random is the worst loot policy.  It rewards effort unevenly and can give more rewards to lower contributors, sometimes continuosly.  If you're going to use random then the guild really needs to be a tight knit group of people who really look out for each other and are willing to make sacrifices if its in the best interest of the whole.  Its hard to find a large group of people willing to be that giving.<br>
<br>
Officer awarded loot can work, if the officers are fair and even handed.  If they know the membership well and know what the needs of the membership are.  However, many times officer awarded loot can degenerate into politics, which tends to undermine the faith of the membership in the fairness and even handedness of the awards.  Also, you'll sometimes have particularly selfish or self centered people make a huge fuss because they didn't get something they thought they had coming, which causes a lot of drama with in the guild.  It can work, but its hard to administer.<br>
<br>
Point systems work and tend to be the system the least open to challenges of unfairness or politics.  They also tend to really over load the people who attend raids the most with more loot than they need.  Rather than having gear spread out somewhat equally amongst the membership with perhaps a few of the choicest pieces on your strongest raid contributors, what can often happen is you'll get a core crew of raiders who get upgrade after upgrade while those with a lower attendance receive fewer upgrades and receive less desirable items.  Its fair, but not necessarily in the long term best interests of the guild in that the core raiders will consistantly receive small upgrades while those for whom it would have been a huge upgrade go without.  This is particularly true when the items involved are no drop.<br>
<br>
 <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=raunstoncutter>RaunStoncutter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 289<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/9/03 11:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.liquid2k.com/raunstonecutter/bunnyhop.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Raid loot policies and guild progression</span><hr size=1> Loot decisions go in cycles.  I personally believe that you should merit all loot.  Up to a point though.<br>
<br>
If you are on your first Kael Arena raid and a quest item drops, I think it's important to merit them so people get used to it.  Although the hard part is comming up with a way to value merit.<br>
<br>
At the same time, if your guild is clearing for vindicator, and some piece of quest armor drops, it's ok to random it, unless there is a real need for it.<br>
<br>
Or, there's always good ole DKP..../not touching that one with a 10' pole<br>
<br>
Loot is good because it's a reward for a challenge, and allows you the opertunity to improve and seek greater challenges.  At the same time, Like Haas points out, it can easily shred a guild to pieces.  But I do agree, full random, and officer decisions suck =/  <br>
<br>
Best of luck to you on your journey =) <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=31658">Raun Stonecutter</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.swordoffate.com">&lt;Sword of Fate&gt;</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
