<br>
It's where you see the same group of people (who go on ever raid mind you) get essentially every peice of worth while loot.<br>
<br>
Example - killing the CS dragon, CoCW drops, you have many melee there, quite a few who are wearing FBSS or equal level haste.  Several who have CoF (and don't want CoCW), and maybe one or two who already have equal haste, but want the cloak for the other stats.  Obviously the people who have FBSS level haste need it the most (it's the largest upgrade for them, and for guild, the people who already have equivalent level haste will not make a bit of diff to a raid if they have whatever cloak they have on now, or this other cloak with some extra +mana).  Yet, somehow, the cloak ends up going to the one person who already has similar level haste, and just wanted it for the stats.  Why?  Because they are in the magical &quot;top 10&quot; who much receive anything remotely good if they have any interest in it.<br>
<br>
Now, I'm not trying to say that those who raid all the time should get the same amount or less then other people, who don't raid as much.  But say I've been raiding hard with the guild for 6 months, and someone else (same class) has been for 8 months (since guild start) and they are in the &quot;top 10&quot; because of those two months.  Sure, they deserve more loot them me over all (they had two months to get it also) but they don't deserve to get all of the best items for that class that drop, even when they are minor upgrades while I get nothing but scrap hand me downs.<br>
<br>
That's sorta where I see a well balanced DKP system comeing into play.  People who raid the most will get the items that they really need, but will not have enough points to gobble up everything that is a minor upgrade while the rest of the guild sits on their thumbs and rotates watching zone after zone go by with the same people getting everything (or most everything).<br>
<br>
DKP can also reinforce the &quot;top 10&quot; thing, if you give out lots of points for raids, and have relatively low item costs then those top 10 will get 90% of the loot, things that are minor upgrades to them but might be drastic upgrades to someone else, who has say, 5 less DKP or something.<br>
<br>
As soon as you lower the rewarded points for a raid, and/or up the item costs what you will start to see is that the top ten will start saving their points, they aren't going to spend points on some neck slot with +5 more HP if it means they might not get that really sweet weapon they have been wanting, so you get someone else who gets that item and it's +55 extra hp, 10 save all, whatever.  A substantial increase rather then a minor one.  You also have more people in general happy in the guild, and stick to the &quot;more put in = more you take out&quot;.<br>
<br>
Only thing with DKP is you need people who will keep the database updated, and you need to let everyone know when you start it that item costs and raid rewards might not be set in stone yet as you work out the kinks.<br>
<br>
As many have said (and mostly rightly so) pure /random really tends to blow.  Sometimes you get lucky, sometimes you don't, and there are some people who always seem to win the randoms, and others who always seem to loose.  The one benefit to pure random is there is never an issue over who gets it, and if your guild members have patience you all can (eventually) get what you want, with no possible favortism other then by EQ's random number generator.<br>
<br>
An interesting idea for a loot system I have had runs basically like this:<br>
1) anyone can lead a raid, to anywhere, whenever they want.<br>
2) all loot will be assigned by the raid leader to anyone the raid leader sees fit (for any reason).<br>
3) raid attendance is not required.<br>
4) coercing people (or trying to) into joining a raid is not allowed.<br>
<br>
ideally what this would lead to would be people not attending raids (or leaving raids early) of someone who is a real dick about loot distro, there by weeding out the morons... sort of natural selection, in a raiding/loot distro world.  Also, if anyone is unhappy with the amount of loot they are getting, all they need to do is lead more raids, and assign loot fairly enough that people don't feel they are just hogging everything to themselves.<br>
<br>
However, what it would probably lead to is no one going to a raid untill it was lead by themselves or a &quot;buddy&quot; of theirs, lots of people whining that they can't lead a raid and aren't getting any loot if they don't, lots of greedy folk who try to lead raid after raid assigning only to their own personal &quot;top 10&quot; etc... but if you have a really friendly guild this idea might work, I've not had a possibility to test it out much.<br>
<br>
The other thing is mobs/raids that you just can't plan, because if someone spots it you need to rush or another guild will grab it.  On these it obviously would not do to have it be whoever first spotted it, you'd end up with 50 checkers all with hotkeys &quot;/gu Zlandi up, i called it, it's my raid!&quot; or whatever mobs you are fighting/spotting for.  So a rotation of sorts could work on these, people sign up for the mob to lead it.  a list of sorts... if someone gets poor attendance (not enough to kill it, so you lose to another guild) say 3 times then you can yank their privilidge to lead that raid for a month, or two, or something to keep guild from loseing it all time.  Again, if you have a reasonable guild then this shouldn't be too much of an issue.<br>
<br>
The other bit is people who would be fair at distro'ing loot but are lacking in leadership skills.  What you could do is allow anyone to &quot;claim loot distro right&quot; for a raid, but always have one of several people lead the raid.  That would help keep consistancy of leadership, while retaining the beneficial loot distro atmosphere.  Or allow sort of &quot;pinch raid leaders&quot; where the loot person can elect someone else to lead the raid, and then do loot but no leading themselves.<br>
<br>
Sorry the post is this long, but loot tends to be a huge problem in this game and I'm always interested in seeing what people think about diff systems, and wouldn't mind seeing what people say bout the little one i have here (I have never seen it implemented on a large scale for a guild, meaning more then just a couple raids like that, because no one really considors it seriously).  I have a feeling though that it is an idea that looks alright on paper, but would not be put into practice how it was intended (think true marxist social theory vs. the USSR, different to the point of being largely unrelated, but still catagorised by many people, rightly or wrongly, as being &quot;communism&quot; and thought of as being equal).  Sorry to bring RL political mentions into it, but it's the only example I could think of off the top of my head of something that was one way in theory, and got carried out completely differently.<br>
<br>
Anyway, hope your guild finds a system that keeps everyone happy, not a whole lot sucks more in EQ then loot issues ripping up a good guild.  and again sorry for lenght ^_^;; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=diedraxev>DiedraXev</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/03 4:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=11>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Raid loot policies and guild progression</span><hr size=1> another thought upon rereading the origonal post.  &quot;Need&quot; tends to be defined in different ways by different people, which can lead to problems.<br>
<br>
Some people define &quot;need&quot; as &quot;what would help the guild the most&quot; and other people define &quot;need&quot; as &quot;who will this be the biggest upgrade for?&quot;<br>
<br>
I am going to assume that it is fairly obvious that a guild as a whole needs to have several things to get very far.  at least one cleric epic, on an active cleric, and at least one (if not several) well equipped tanks who are also active.  So, the one defination of &quot;need&quot; (guild-centric) would go for upgradeing the tanks first, and getting clerics their epics before others (at least until guild has one or more at their disposial).<br>
<br>
The other way people define &quot;need&quot; would be basically whoever has the crappiest stuff gets the best stuff.<br>
<br>
Sometimes people use sort of a hybrid defination where they want it to do as much help as it can to the guild but also be as large of an upgrade as possible.<br>
<br>
At anyrate, if your guild is having problems with what &quot;need&quot; means, I'd suggest hammering out what defination of &quot;need&quot; your guild wants to use with your guild, as it can validly mean several different things, includeing I am sure things I have not mentioned here.<br>
<br>
