<br>
True enough, but it can lead to overloading those working harder/more with significantly more loot than they need.  One idea that seems to work is to add a counter balance to it.  The guild I'm in uses a ratio.  The number of raids you've attended is divided by the number of loot items you've recieved.  You earn points for raid attendance as normal, however each item that drops is assigned a point value which will be deducted from your total points if you are allowed to loot.  If more than one person is interested in the item then the one with the highest ratio (that is the person with the fewest looted items for the number of raids they've attended) is given the opportunity to loot.<br>
<br>
Here is an example:  Jack has been to 10 raids and has looted 3 items.  Jill has been to 7 raids and has looted 1 item.  Jack's ratio is 3.  Jill's ratio is 7.  If a 4 point item drops and both Jack and Jill have at least 4 points accumulated and want the drop, Jill will get it before Jack because of her ratio.<br>
<br>
This encourages people to only bid on those upgrades they find particularly desireable since they may not have a high enough ratio, even if they have the points, for something they really want the next raid.  Fewer loots overall increases the chances you'll get what you really want when it drops.<br>
<br>
Yes, sometimes people with more accumulated points won't get their heart's desire because someone with fewer points has a higher ratio.  But more points will still lead to more loot in the long run.  <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
